<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900625-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>900625-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Friction Division Products Inc.:   Firm to Pay $285,000 Fine   To Settle Agency Charges</HL><DATE>06/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>BUILDING MATERIALS (BLD)</IN><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><LP>   Friction Division Products Inc. agreed to pay $285,000 infines as part of a settlement of Labor Department charges ofasbestos-related, workplace health violations.   The Trenton, N.J., maker of brake pads and linings forcars and trucks also agreed to pay as much as $1.7 millionmore in fines if it violates a consent order by the federalappeals court in Philadelphia, the department's OccupationalSafety and Health Administration said. The company furtheragreed to take a series of actions aimed at abating seriousasbestos-control problems, OSHA said.</LP><TEXT>   Last July, OSHA proposed fines of $2.7 million against thecompany, the largest ever proposed for health violations.   The company agreed to the settlement without admittingguilt, OSHA said.   Friction Division said that its president was the onlyperson authorized to comment on the settlement and that hewasn't immediately available.</TEXT></DOC>